# API Design Conventions

## Route Structure

Next.js App Router API routes follow resource-based naming:

```
src/app/api/
├── users/route.ts          GET (list), POST (create)
├── users/[id]/route.ts     GET (single), PATCH (update), DELETE
├── events/route.ts         GET (list)
├── rsvp/route.ts           POST (create/update)
├── report/route.ts         POST (create)
└── admin/route.ts          Protected admin endpoints
```

## Request/Response Pattern

Every API route handler follows this pattern:

```typescript
import { getServerSession } from "next-auth";
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { z } from "zod";
import * as Sentry from "@sentry/nextjs";
import { authOptions } from "@/lib/authOptions";

const requestSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1).max(100),
});

export async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
  try {
    const session = await getServerSession(authOptions);
    if (!session?.user) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "Niet ingelogd" }, { status: 401 });
    }

    const body = await req.json();
    const parsed = requestSchema.safeParse(body);
    if (!parsed.success) {
      return NextResponse.json(
        { error: "Ongeldige invoer", details: parsed.error.issues },
        { status: 400 },
      );
    }

    const result = await SomeService.create(parsed.data);
    return NextResponse.json({ data: result }, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    Sentry.captureException(error);
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: "Er ging iets mis" },
      { status: 500 },
    );
  }
}
```

## Status Codes

| Code | When |
|---|---|
| 200 | Successful GET, PATCH |
| 201 | Successful POST (resource created) |
| 204 | Successful DELETE (no body) |
| 400 | Validation failure (Zod) |
| 401 | Not authenticated |
| 403 | Authenticated but not authorized |
| 404 | Resource not found |
| 409 | Conflict (duplicate) |
| 429 | Rate limit exceeded |
| 500 | Unexpected server error (log to Sentry, never expose internals) |

## Error Response Format

```typescript
// Client errors — include actionable message in Dutch
{ error: "E-mailadres is al in gebruik" }

// Validation errors — include field details
{ error: "Ongeldige invoer", details: zodError.issues }

// Server errors — generic message, details go to Sentry
{ error: "Er ging iets mis" }
```

## Rules

- Keep route handlers thin — delegate to `src/lib/services/`
- Always validate input with Zod before passing to services
- Always check auth with `getServerSession(authOptions)` on protected routes
- Always wrap in try/catch with `Sentry.captureException(error)`
- Return Dutch error messages for user-facing errors
- Use `select` in Prisma queries to return only needed fields
- Add `take` (limit) to list queries to prevent unbounded results
